\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator considered the original application\'2C first evaluator\'E2\'80\'99s report\'2C the recommendation of the HEQC and the representation made and concluded that\'2C although the Institution has put in effort to address the concerns raised\'2C it was evident from the representation that there were still important concerns. The evaluator recommended that the programme should not be accredited.\line \line In the HEQC recommendation\'2C it was stated that Damelin was not clear on how the programme purpose would be achieved as only 15 credits were dedicated to Project Management which was the qualifier in the programme. In their response\'2C Damelin has provided a revised SAQA document\'2C a revised curriculum structure\'2C revised module outlines and a revised list of prescribed and recommended textbooks. The revised curriculum includes eight compulsory modules comprising 15 credits each. All of the modules have a Project Management focus as indicated by the programme qualifier. The evaluator\'2C however\'2C noted that with the exception of two modules\'2C the same textbook is prescribed for all the other modules. The evaluator found this untenable. \line \line The HEQC had also stated that\'2C while there was a WIL component of 15 credits indicated\'2C very little detail had been provided on the management of WIL and the integration of this component in the curriculum of the programme.  In the representation\'2C the Institution has submitted the Experiential Learning \'28WIL\'29 Policy\'2C EL \'28WIL\'29 Manager Job Description\'2C EL Coordinator Job Description and a revised EL outline. The representation confirmed that experiential learning will be managed from both the Educor Head Office and at each Damelin campus by the EL Coordinator and EL Guardian Lecturers. The EL Manager will be responsible for the strategic direction and institutional practices of EL. The EL Coordinator manages the execution of EL for all programmes at a particular campus. In addition\'2C the EL Coordinator liaises with Head Office by providing tracking and periodic reports\'2C as well as coordinating the assessment and moderation of the portfolios of evidence. Each programme has a subject matter expert who also acts as an EL guardian lecturer. The evaluator noted that Damelin is not consistent with the use of terminology\'2C e.g. EL vs WIL\'2C EL Manager vs WIL Learning Manager\'2C research project vs project management plan\'2C EL guardian lecturer vs lecturer\'2C etc. In addition\'2C the evaluator pointed out that it was indicated that 10\'25 of the portfolios of evidence will be moderated by a subject matter expert\'2C whilst the Experiential Learning Policy indicates that EL was externally moderated. The Institution must give clarification on the process of external moderation as applicable to EL. \line \line The HEQC had\'2C furthermore\'2C pointed out that Damelin had failed to explain how students with low numeracy or with no background in Finance would be able to manage this programme given the Accounting and Statistics modules in the programme.  In the representation\'2C Damelin has confirmed that all Finance-related modules have been removed from the revised curriculum. The evaluator\'2C however\'2C noted that one of the modules of the revised curriculum is Project Resource\'2C Cost and Procurement Management\'2C which implies numerical skills. Project Management as such implies calculations and numerical skills. The Institution needs to clarify how this would be dealt with. \line \line Another concern raised in the HEQC recommendation was that formative and summative assessment\'2C as outlined in the Assessment Policy\'2C had not been clarified as well as the management of assessments at the different sites of delivery.  The evaluator\'2C in analysing the documents submitted\'2C found that the Damelin Assessment Policy gave a clear distinction between the different types of assessment\'2C including formative and summative assessments. The representation confirmed that assessment is managed by the Dean of Operations. The tasks of the Dean include\'3A provision of academic leadership in assessment design and the constructive alignment of assessments to learning outcomes\'2C responsible for managing internal and external moderation processes\'2C responsible for quality assurance of all assessment practices at site\'2C brand and group level and ensure deadlines are met\'2C ensure a secure assessment system and protocols and renew as needed for both contact delivery and distance brands\'2C etc. The evaluator found the response acceptable.\line \line The HEQC had also stated that Damelin had not provided an explanation of how it intends to implement assessment and teaching and learning ensuring equivalence of provisioning across multiple campuses. In response\'2C Damelin has listed several strategic goals regarding teaching and learning across all campuses. For example\'2C the creation and maintenance of a well-resourced teaching and learning environment in terms of facilities and infrastructure\'2C on a sustainable basis\'3B the effective use of systems\'2C including learning analytics to profile students and track their learning achievements\'3B adequate and accessible ICT facilities for staff and students\'2C including the provision of teaching and learning media in all teaching venues\'2C etc. It is also noted that the policies submitted apply to all campuses. These documents are available for all lecturers across all campuses. The evaluator found that uncertainties have been addressed.\line \line Finally\'2C the recommendation had pointed out that the Institution had failed to clarified the different types of assessments mentioned and whether formative assessment marks count towards the summative total. The supporting evidence submitted in response included the Assessment Policy and the Damelin Assessment Guidelines. According to the module outlines\'2C four assessments are applicable to all modules\'2C excluding the EL module. The formative assessments comprise the group assignment\'2C individual assignment and the test. The summative assessment comprises the final examination. The evaluator found that this meets the minimum required standards.\line \line The Directorate recommends that the programme should be accredited with conditions.\cell \pard 

